{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598414"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:37:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:37:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15473"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15473"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.49,0.29,0,0.06,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8164"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61521"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8164","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8164"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15473"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46974"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6746"},{"type":"tags","id":"7883"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19778"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19782"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61521"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image shows histological findings from a patient with allergic sinusitis. Numerous eosinophil granulocytes are present.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is most likely to be present in this histological specimen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Charcot-Leyden crystals","Mucus plugs","Epithelial pearls","Plasma cell aggregates","Neutrophil clusters"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn allergic conditions with significant eosinophilia, \u003Cstrong\u003ECharcot-Leyden crystals\u003C/strong\u003E are commonly observed. These hexagonal bipyramidal crystals form from lysophospholipase, an enzyme released during eosinophil degradation. They are characteristic findings in allergic conditions including asthma, allergic sinusitis, and parasitic infections.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMucus plugs\u003C/strong\u003E are more commonly seen in bronchial specimens from asthma patients. \u003Cstrong\u003EEpithelial pearls\u003C/strong\u003E are typically associated with squamous cell carcinoma. \u003Cstrong\u003EPlasma cell aggregates\u003C/strong\u003E are more characteristic of chronic inflammation or autoimmune conditions. \u003Cstrong\u003ENeutrophil clusters\u003C/strong\u003E are typically seen in acute bacterial infections rather than allergic conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Charcot-Leyden crystals are degradation products of eosinophils commonly seen in allergic conditions.","Eosinophil breakdown products form characteristic microscopic findings in allergic inflammation."],"references":["\u0022Charcot-Leyden crystals, HE 1\u0022 by Patho is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license. https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Charcot-Leyden_crystals,_HE_1.jpg","Erjef\u00e4lt JS. Anatomical and histopathological approaches to asthma phenotyping. Respir Med. 2023 Apr-May;210:107168. doi: 10.1016/j.rmed.2023.107168. Epub 2023 Feb 21. PMID: 36822489","Ueki S, Miyabe Y, Yamamoto Y, Fukuchi M, Hirokawa M, Spencer LA, Weller PF. Charcot-Leyden Crystals in Eosinophilic Inflammation: Active Cytolysis Leads to Crystal Formation. Curr Allergy Asthma Rep. 2019 Jun 15;19(8):35. doi: 10.1007/s11882-019-0868-0. Erratum in: Curr Allergy Asthma Rep. 2019 Jul 13;19(8):38. doi: 10.1007/s11882-019-0875-1. PMID: 31203469; PMCID: PMC6952074.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46974"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15473"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21163"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21163"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/eOQPgcpKzl7Q3ivsLH0v3jT6XgD0Qz.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/eOQPgcpKzl7Q3ivsLH0v3jT6XgD0Qz.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1000}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/46974"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-15T18:13:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T18:15:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8164"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61521"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","pos